thread.title: J.P. Morgan jumps on profits; Wells Fargo slips on revenue miss
thread.title_full: J.P. Morgan jumps on profits; Wells Fargo slips on revenue miss - MarketWatch

author: By     Sue Chang   and   Sara Sjolin
title: J.P. Morgan jumps on profits; Wells Fargo slips on revenue miss
text:
AFP/Getty Images J.P. Morgan is slated to release quarterly results on Tuesday. These are the stocks making notable moves in Tuesday trade:
Gainers J.P. Morgan JPM, +1.55% jumped Tuesday after the bank reported second-quarter results of $1.54 a share, 10 cents better than analysts’ estimates, as the bank benefited from better lending and a merger boom .
Shares of Amazon.com Inc. AMZN, +2.72% jumped in premarket trade, flirting with record territory , after Wells Fargo analyst Matt Nemer said growth expectations for the e-commerce giant are too conservative, reiterating his stock rating of outperform and raising his stock valuation to $495 to $520 from $421 to $450.
Shares of Micron Technology Inc. MU, +0.23% surged 12% ahead of the bell after a report late Monday that China’s Tsinghua Unigroup Ltd. has submitted a bid to buy out the U.S. memory-chip maker for $23 billion.
Starbucks Corp. SBUX, +2.07% added 0.6% in thin premarket trade after the coffee chain struck a deal to push into sub-Saharan Africa next year .
Johnson & Johnson JNJ, +0.74% added 0.7% in premarket trade after the drug-and-consumer company reported a better-than-expected second-quarter profit and adjusted its full-year outlook higher.
Decliner Wells Fargo WFC, +1.18% sank in premarket trade after the bank reported profits that were in line with Wall Street estimates of $1.03 a share, but revenues that missed expectations. Read: How do Wells Fargo and J.P. Morgan shape up ahead of earnings?
Tickers to Watch Yum Brands YUM, +0.28% is expected to post second-quarter earnings of 64 cents a share, down from 73 cents a share in the same period a year before.
CSX Corp. CSX, -0.72% is expected to post second-quarter earnings of 53 cents a share, unchanged from the year-earlier period.
Starbucks Corp. SBUX, +2.07% could also move after the coffee chain struck a deal to push into sub-Saharan Africa next year.
Oil-related companies moved lower ahead of the bell after crude prices CLQ5, -0.15% slumped on the back of the Iranian nuclear deal . Exxon Mobil Corp. XOM, +0.24% and Halliburton Co. HAL, +1.31% each shaved off 0.4% ahead of the bell, while ConocoPhillips COP, -0.34% dropped 1.2%.
After Monday’s close, Navient Corp. NAVI, -0.05% projected quarterly earnings below analysts’ consensus estimate and cut its outlook for the year. The student-loan management and servicing company forecast core earnings of 40 cents a share for the second quarter, and $1.85 a share for the year. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had expected 55 cents a share for the quarter, and $2.19 a share for the year.
Valero Energy Corp. VLO, +1.55% said Monday its board had approved an additional $2.5 billion stock-buyback program. It will also pay its regular dividend of 40 cents a share to shareholders of record as of Aug. 4.
Also late Monday, The Wall Street Journal reported that China’s Tsinghua Unigroup Ltd. has submitted a bid to buy out memory-chip maker Micron Technology Inc. MU, +0.23% for $23 billion. Micron shares jumped 10% ahead of the bell Tuesday.
